<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-10-23T07:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-10-23T07:00:00-05:00" n="302" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d302">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/13319</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Denmark</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_EMF1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Egan</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Copenhagen</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-10-23T13:00:00+01:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">October 23, 1917, 1 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received October 24, 3
                                    a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>1464. During a conversation with an official Austrian temporarily in
                                Copenhagen, I asked: “Why do you not surrender, then also food
                                troubles would come to an end?” Instead of receiving the suggestion
                                with disdain he replied simply: “We cannot surrender. The <pb facs="0352" n="278" xml:id="pg_278"/> Italians want Trieste and
                                Fiume and the entire littoral to cut us off from the sea, to which
                                we could never consent.”</p>
                            <closer>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>